ions, Abigail Gillman juxtaposes translations within each that sought to achieve similar goals through differing means. As she details the history of successive translations, we gain new insight into the opportunities and problems the Bible posed for different generations and gain a new perspective on modern German Jewish history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aJudaismzGermanyxHistoryyModern period, 1750- 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aAshkenaz.  aGerman Jews.  aHaskalah.  aHebrew Bible.  aMartin Luther.  aMoses Mendelssohn.  aTargum.  aYiddish.  atranslation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226477862423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226477862/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles